{{Hinduism}}
'''Sri Anantazhwar''' was a disciple of [[Ramanuja]] and a 12th century [[Vaishnava]] figure of India.<ref name=Venkateswara>{{cite book|title=Sri Venkateshwara|author=Shantha Nair|publisher=Jaico Publishing House, 07-Jan-2014 - Religion - 280 pages}}</ref>
== Legend of Venkateswara ==
The story goes that Ramanuja once asked Anantalwar to raise a flower garden for the Lord on the [[Venkateswara_Temple,_Tirumala|Tirumala hill]], that is [[Venkateswara]]. Anantalwar abided by the request and went upon raising a garden. He took the help of his pregnant wife who found it difficult to do the manual labor from time to time. Lord Venkateswara having seen the trouble of the lady assumed the form of a young lad and helped her out. On one occasion when this came to the notice of Anantalwar, the latter was furious and he hit the lad with a crowbar. The lad then disappeared but when Anantalwar visited the god in Tirumala, he found that the Lord was bleeding from the chin. He at once realised that it was the Lord who had helped his wife and regretted his behavior. He applied green camphor for the wound. Lord Venkateswara was impressed with Anantalwar's devotion and not only forgave him but also told him that he would display the green camphor forever as a mark of Anantalwar's devotion. Thus green camphor is applied to the Lord's chin to this day during the rituals.<ref name=Venkateswara/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tirumalesa.com/why-is-green-camphor-applied-to-lord-venkateswaras-chin-in-tirumala-temple-everyday|title=why-is-green-camphor-applied-to-lord-venkateswaras-chin-in-tirumala-temple-everyday|website=www.tirumalesa.com|accessdate=2018-10-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tirumalatirupatiyatra.in/tirumala/about-tirumala/inside-temple/anantalwar-crow-bar|title=Anantalwar Crowbar|website=tirumalatirupatiyatra.in|accessdate=2018-10-31}}</ref>
== References == {{reflist}}
[[Category:Vaishnavism]] [[Category:Indian Hindu religious leaders]]

'''Coelia Concordia''' was the last [[Vestal Virgin|vestal virgin]] in history and the last ''Vestalis Maxima'' or Chief Vestal.<ref name="Cooper1999">{{cite book|author=Kate Cooper|title=The Virgin and the Bride: Idealized Womanhood in Late Antiquity|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QVvn8vUMZdIC&pg=PA100|year=1999|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=978-0-674-93950-9|pages=100–}}</ref> The [[Temple of Vesta]] was closed in 391 by the [[Roman Emperor|Roman emperor]] [[Theodosius I]], and Coelia stepped down from her post in 394. She converted to [[Christianity]] later in her life, and died twelve years later.<ref name="LefkowitzFant2005">{{cite book|author1=Mary R. Lefkowitz|author2=Maureen B. Fant|title=Women's Life in Greece and Rome: A Source Book in Translation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LV-FPLMeHgoC&pg=PA306|date=23 August 2005|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|isbn=978-0-8018-8310-1|pages=306–}}</ref>
