{{for|the Oklahoma radio station|KACO (FM)}} {{Italic title}} The '''''kaco''''' is a type of [[shamanism|shamanistic]] drum of the [[Ainu people]], primarily those of [[Sakhalin Island]].<ref name="Pentikäinen1996">{{cite book|author=Juha Pentikäinen|title=Shamanism and Northern Ecology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rvf0V3z-6asC&pg=PA305|accessdate=24 August 2012|year=1996|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=978-3-11-014186-3|pages=305–}}</ref>
==Construction== The instrument is made of a wooden branch of willow or larch bent into an ellipse with a membrane of [[musk deer]] skin; the drum beater is covered in [[dogskin]].<ref name="Ohnuki-Tierney1981">{{cite book|author=Emiko Ohnuki-Tierney|title=Illness and Healing among the Sakhalin Ainu: A symbolic interpretation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OTo9AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA75|accessdate=24 August 2012|date=31 August 1981|publisher=CUP Archive|isbn=978-0-521-23636-2|pages=75–}}</ref>
==Etymology== The word ''kaco'' may be a loan-word from the [[Orok language]].<ref name="Pentikäinen1996">{{cite book|author=Juha Pentikäinen|title=Shamanism and Northern Ecology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rvf0V3z-6asC&pg=PA305|accessdate=24 August 2012|year=1996|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=978-3-11-014186-3|pages=305–}}</ref> The drum may be more formally called ''senisteh'', a word referring to charms in general.<ref name="Ohnuki-Tierney1981">{{cite book|author=Emiko Ohnuki-Tierney|title=Illness and Healing among the Sakhalin Ainu: A symbolic interpretation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OTo9AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA75|accessdate=24 August 2012|date=31 August 1981|publisher=CUP Archive|isbn=978-0-521-23636-2|pages=75–}}</ref>
