{{Use British English|date=October 2018}} {{EngvarB|date=November 2013}} {{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}} {{Pie chart |thumb = right |caption = Religion in Northern Ireland - 2011<ref name=2011ksdata /> |label1 = [[Roman Catholic Church]] |value1 = 45.76 |color1 = DarkOrchid |label2 = [[Presbyterian Church in Ireland|Presbyterian Church]] |value2 = 24.06 |color2 = DodgerBlue |label3 = [[Church of Ireland|Anglican Church]] |value3 = 13.74 |color3 = DeepSkyBlue |label4 = [[Methodist Church in Ireland|Methodist Church]] |value4 = 3.00 |color4 = Turquoise |label5 = Other Christian |value5 = 5.76 |color5 = Aquamarine |label6 = Other religion |value6 = 0.82 |color6 = Chartreuse |label7 = [[Irreligious|Non-religious]] |value7 = 4.11 |color7 = WhiteSmoke |label8 = Not stated |value8 = 2.75 |color8 = Black }}
{{Pie chart |thumb = right |caption = Religion raised in - 2011<ref name=2011ksdata /> |label1 = Protestantism |value1 = 48.4 |color1 = DodgerBlue |label2 = Roman Catholicism |value2 = 45.1 |color2 = DarkOrchid |label3 = Other |value3 = 0.9 |color3 = Chartreuse |label4 = None |value4 = 5.6 |color4 = WhiteSmoke }}
[[Christianity]] is the largest '''religion in Northern Ireland'''. According to a 2007 [[Tearfund]] survey, [[Northern Ireland]] was the most religious part of the UK, with 45% regularly attending [[church service|church]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6520463.stm |title=Tearfund Survey|publisher=BBC}}</ref>
The Catholic Church has seen a small growth in adherents, while the other Christian groups have seen a small decrease.
There are also small Hindu, Sikh, Muslim, Buddhist and Jewish communities. [[Belfast]] has a synagogue, a [[gurdwara]], a mosque and two Hindu temples. There is another gurdwara in [[Derry]].
