'''Dr. Roger J. Stronstad''' is a [[Canada|Canadian]] [[Pentecostalism|Pentecostal]] [[Bible]] scholar and [[theology|theologian]].<ref name="Walston2003">{{cite book|last=Walston|first=Rick|title=The Speaking in Tongues Controversy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v-9pakVOsD0C&pg=PA47|accessdate=25 September 2011|date=July 2003|publisher=Xulon Press|isbn=978-1-59160-762-5|pages=47–}}</ref> He is an Associate Professor in Bible and Theology at [[Summit Pacific College]] (formerly Western Pentecostal Bible College) in [[Abbotsford, British Columbia]].He has also published six books.

== Works ==

In ''The Charismatic Theology of St. Luke'' (1984), he argues for a Pentecostal interpretation of [[Gospel of Luke|Luke]]-[[Acts of the Apostles|Acts]]. He contends that Luke believed the gift of the Spirit was vocational, rather than soteriological or ethical, i.e. the [[Holy Spirit]] was given to empower them to be witnesses, rather than to bring them [[salvation]]. This book has been translated in French (La théologie charismatique de St Luc).

In ''Spirit, Scripture and Theology'' (1995), Stronstad surveys Pentecostal [[hermeneutics]] (methods of biblical interpretation), examining the views of [[Gordon Fee|Gordon D. Fee]], [[Howard M. Ervin]] and [[William H. Menzies]]. Again he returns to Luke-Acts to formulate his own hermeneutical approach.

In ''The Prophethood of All Believers'' (1999), he builds on his interpretation of Luke-Acts, focusing on the Holy Spirit as the giver of [[prophecy|prophetic]] gifts to the [[Christian Church|Church]].

He is also co-editor (with French L. Arrington and Timothy Jenney) of the ''Life in the Spirit New Testament Commentary'' (2003).

