{{God}} '''Theocentricism''' is the belief that [[God]] is the central aspect to our existence, as opposed to [[anthropocentrism]] or [[existentialism]].{{citation needed|date=May 2012}} In this view, meaning and value of actions done to people or the environment are attributed to God. The tenets of theocentrism, such as humility, respect, moderations, selflessness, and mindfulness, can lend themselves towards a form of environmentalism.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Hoffman|first=Andrew J.|author2=Sandelands, Lloyd E. |title=GETTING RIGHT WITH NATURE Anthropocentrism, Ecocentrism, and Theocentrism|journal=Organization & Environment|date=June 2005|volume=18|doi=10.1177/1086026605276197|url=http://www.earthgroaning.ca/wp-content/uploads/2012/04/right-nature.pdf|accessdate=17 November 2012| page= 1}}</ref> In modern theology, theocentricism is often linked with [[stewardship]] and [[environmental ethics]] or [[Creation care]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Theology of Nature: Trinitarian Paradigms for Ecology|url=http://www.uocc.ca/pdf/theology/Theology%20of%20Nature.pdf|work=uocc.ca|publisher=Ukrainian Orthodox Church of Canada|accessdate=5 December 2013}}</ref> It is the belief that human beings should look after the world as guardians and therefore in the way God wants them to. Humans should be considerate to all, from animals to plants to humans themselves. It maintains that human beings are merely here for a short time and should be looking after the world for future generations.<ref>{{cite web|last=Howell|first=John|title=Theological and Ecological Ethics|url=http://www.cws.org.nz/files/Ecological_Ethics_Essay_29May09.pdf|work=cws.org|publisher=Christian World Service|accessdate=5 December 2013}}</ref>
In [[Christian theology]], theocentricism has sometimes been used to describe theologies that focus on [[God the Father]], as opposed to those that focus on [[Christ]] ([[Christocentric]]) or the [[Holy Spirit (Christianity)|Holy Spirit]] (Pneumocentric). Theocentrism was a key element of the [[Christology]] of [[Saint Augustine]].<ref>''Orthodox readings of Augustine'' by George E. Demacopoulos, Aristotle Papanikolaou 2008 {{ISBN|0-88141-327-5}} page 271</ref> This view is resisted among some theologians on the grounds that it poses a challenge to trinity. One of these theologians is Carl Baaten who said, "If one can speak of God who is really God apart from Christ, there is indeed no reason for the doctrine of the Trinity. Some kind of Unitarianism will do the job."<ref>{{cite journal|last=Knitter|first=Paul F.|title=Theocentric Christology: Defended and Transcended|journal=Journal of Ecumenical Studies|year=1987|volume=24|issue=1|pages=42–43}}</ref> Paul F. Knitter, in his defense as a Theocentric Christian, said it depends on how the unity between God and Jesus Christ within trinity is seen. He says that, "we cannot so neatly or exclusively affirm that the Logos/Christ is Jesus. The 'incarnating' activity of the Logos is actualized in but not restricted to Jesus. The God manifested in and as Jesus of Nazareth is the only true God".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Knitter|first=Paul F.|title=Theocentric Christology: Defended and Transcended|journal=Journal of Ecumenical Studies|year=1987|volume=24|issue=1|pages=52}}</ref>
However, the term can be confusing because ''theocentrism'' can also refer to a theology that does not center on any one person of the Trinity, but rather emphases the entire Godhead as a whole. Theologies that center on the Father are sometimes referred to as ''paterocentric'' instead.<ref name="patero">{{cite web|url=http://thegospelcoalition.org/themelios/article/christocentrism_an_asymmetrical_trinitarianism|title=Christocentrism: An Asymmetrical Trinitarianism?}}</ref>
It is popular with [[Christianity]], [[Judaism]] and [[Islam]].
==See also== * [[Anthropocentrism]] * [[biocentrism (ethics)|Biocentrism]] * [[Ecocentrism]] * [[Intrinsic value (animal ethics)]] * [[Sentiocentrism]] * [[Speciesism]] * [[Technocentrism]]
