{{Infobox scientist | name = William Hewat McLeod | image = | caption = | pseudonym = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1932|08|02|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Feilding]], [[New Zealand]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|2009|07|20|1932|08|02}} | death_place = [[Dunedin]], [[New Zealand]] | fields = Historian | nationality = | workplaces = | patrons = | education = [[School of Oriental and African Studies]] | thesis_title = The life and doctrine of Gurū Nānak | thesis_url = | thesis_year = 1965 | doctoral_advisor = <!--(or | doctoral_advisors = )--> | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = | known_for = Sikh history and culture | spouse = Margaret Wylie (m. 1955) | influences = | influenced = | signature =
}}
'''William Hewat "Hew" McLeod''' (2 August 1932 – 20 July 2009) was a New Zealand scholar who wrote about Sikh history and culture. He produced many books and essays on Sikh identity, Sikh history and Sikh theology. His work frequently was a source of controversy.<ref name=guardian-obituary>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/sep/03/w-h-mcleod-obituary | title=WH McLeod | date=3 September 2009 | work=The Guardian | accessdate=26 August 2013| first=Tony | last=Ballantyne}}</ref>
== Personal life == McLeod was born and raised in a farming family near [[Feilding]], in New Zealand's North Island. He met Margaret Wylie in Dunedin during his university studies, and they were married in May 1955. They had four children.<ref name=guardian-obituary />
== Education == McLeod was educated at [[Nelson College]] from 1946 to 1950,<ref name="NCOB register">''Nelson College Old Boys' Register, 1856–2006'', 6th edition</ref> and then at the [[University of Otago]], Dunedin, where he earned a BA and then an MA in history, graduating in 1954.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://shadowsoftime.co.nz/university16.html |title=NZ university graduates 1870–1961: Mc |date= |website= |publisher= |accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref> He then began theological studies and in 1958 joined the New Zealand Presbyterian church's mission to [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], India. At Kharar, in Punjab, he learned the local languages ([[Hindi]] and [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]) and taught English at the Christian Boys secondary school.
Later, he completed a PhD at the School of Oriental and African Studies in London in 1965.<ref name=guardian-obituary />
In 1990 he was awarded a [[Doctor of Letters|DLit]] by the University of London,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.royalsociety.org.nz/organisation/academy/fellowship/obituaries/william-hewat-mcleod/ |title=William Hewat McLeod |date=19 November 2010 |first=Erik |last=Olssen |website= |publisher=Royal Society of New Zealand |accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref> and he was elected a [[Fellow of the Royal Society of New Zealand]] in 1999.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.royalsociety.org.nz/organisation/academy/fellowship/fellows-1919-present/m-o/ |title=The Academy: M–O |date= |website= |publisher=Royal Society of New Zealand |accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref>
== Selected works == * Sikhism ({{ISBN|0140252606}}) * Sikhs and Sikhism ({{ISBN|0195647459}}) * Sikhs of the Khalsa: A History of the Khalsa Rahit ({{ISBN|0195672216}}) * The Sikhs: History, Religion, and Society ({{ISBN|0231068158}}) * Who is a Sikh?: The Problem of Sikh Identity ({{ISBN|0198265484}}) * Historical Dictionary of Sikhism ({{ISBN|0810850885}}) * Essays in Sikh History, Tradition, and Society ({{ISBN|0195682742}}) * Exploring Sikhism: Aspects of Sikh Identity, Culture, and Thought ({{ISBN|0195649028}}) * Guru Nanak and the Sikh Religion ({{ISBN|0198265212}}) * Early Sikh Tradition a Study of the Janam Sakhis ({{ISBN|0198265328}}) * The Evolution of the Sikh Community: Five Essays ({{ISBN|0198265298}}) * The Sikhs of the Punjab ({{ISBN|0853621233}}) * Popular Sikh Art ({{ISBN|0195627911}})
